# Copy to .env and fill in. See docs/DEPLOYMENT.md for the full story on each of these.

# Postgres connection string (Supabase free tier, or any Postgres host).
#
# Get it from Supabase → your project → "Connect" button → "Transaction pooler" tab
# → copy the URI, replace [YOUR-PASSWORD]. Two things that aren't obvious and will
# otherwise cost you an hour (both hit for real building this):
#   1. Supabase's *direct* connection host (db.<ref>.supabase.co) is IPv6-only — on
#      an IPv4-only network it fails outright with P1001. Use the pooler host
#      (aws-*.pooler.supabase.com) instead, which is IPv4.
#   2. The pooler's TLS certificate isn't in Node's default trusted chain — you need
#      `?sslmode=no-verify` on the connection string, or every query fails with
#      "self-signed certificate in certificate chain" (P1011).
# Running `prisma migrate dev`/`deploy` against the *transaction*-mode pooler
# (port 6543) can hang or misbehave — Prisma's migration engine wants a
# session-capable connection. Point DATABASE_URL at the *session* pooler
# (same host, port 5432) just for running migrations, then switch back to the
# transaction pooler (port 6543) for the app itself (better suited to
# many short-lived serverless connections, e.g. on Vercel).
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.xxxxxxxxxxxxx:password@aws-x-xx-xxxx-x.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres?sslmode=no-verify"

# Google AI Studio → https://aistudio.google.com/apikey (free tier)
GEMINI_API_KEY=

# Composio dashboard → https://dashboard.composio.dev/settings
COMPOSIO_API_KEY=
# Composio → Toolkits → Instagram → create an auth config, copy its id
COMPOSIO_INSTAGRAM_AUTH_CONFIG_ID=
# Fixed Composio userId for V1's single local user — any stable string works
COMPOSIO_USER_ID=local-user
